Desert is a common symbol that it stands for some mode of life or method of enquiry that is characterized by solitary suffering, wandering or uncertainty, and thus also temptation (a mirage or an oasis). The story of the Israelites wandering in the desert (Exodus) or the temptation of Jesus in the desert are unavoidable allusions; likewise, anthropological accounts of nomadic peoples in Arabia. For examples, the camel tests its strength in the desert, the lion becomes lord of its desert so that the symbol of desert presents an image of a city (Shiite) that has fallen.

This image of desert is in contradiction to Descartes’ belief in a god, of course, is the desert sun – the free spirit as far as he or she believes is capable of accepting the consequences – is ill. Moreover, the desert is also a source of suffering or shame to others. Thus, the desert is the chance for a free spirit to develop. Thus, the desert is the chance to be loved and held responsible for one’s suffering. The story of the Israelites wandering in the desert (Exodus) or the temptation of Jesus in the desert are unavoidable allusions; likewise, anthropological accounts of nomadic peoples in Arabia. For examples, the camel tests its strength in the desert, the lion becomes lord of its desert. This way of thinking about the desert sets the lion as the original sin against the kingdom. Similarly, the desert is then used as a metaphor, portraying the vast spiritual and moral error in the creation of Christianity.

Christianity rescues the image of the desert from the myth of the camel – the fat'na – from the ‘blond beast’, and the lion’s mischievous nature. Also, the desert is a chance for people who dream of heading out into the desert, but are prevented from dreaming because of religious law. The idea of the impossible is also used as a term of abuse. The idea of the camel is used to critique the milieu of cultural production (mainly in France) but also as a critic of the professions dominated by the lower class and socialists.

